"{\"uid\": \"timeout.com-london-news-the-olympic-parks-iconic-arcelormittal-orbit-will-reopen-as-an-adventure-attraction-next-year-091324\", \"text\": \"\\ud83d\\ude4cAwesome, you are subscribed!  Thanks for subscribing! Look out for your first newsletter in your inbox soon!  The best of London straight to your inbox  We help you navigate a myriad of possibilities. Sign up for our newsletter for the best of the city.  By entering your email address you agree to ourTerms of UseandPrivacy Policyand consent to receive emails from Time Out about news, events, offers and partner promotions.  Awesome, you are subscribed!  Thanks for subscribing! Look out for your first newsletter in your inbox soon!  The best of London for free.  Sign up for our email to enjoy London without spending a thing (as well as some options when you are feeling flush).  D\\u00e9j\\u00e0 vu! We already have this email. Try another?  By entering your email address you agree to ourTerms of UseandPrivacy Policyand consent to receive emails from Time Out about news, events, offers and partner promotions.  London  New operators Zip World are calling the new attraction a 'European first-of-its-kind adventure'  Next to the Walkie Talkie, the Barbican andNo 1 Poultry,the spiralling ArcelorMittal Orbit tower at Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park is one of those London\\u00a0landmarks people love to hate.  Built to mark the London 2012 Olympics, the Orbit is theUK'slargest public sculpture and home to the world's longest tunnel slide. It was projected to see around 350,000 visitors per year but since opening has only had 1.2 million. It's\\u00a0been closed since the start of 2024 due to maintenance work and the previous management contract coming to an end.  ButWelshadventure brand Zip World believes it can boost the Orbit's appeal.\\u00a0It is\\u00a0officially taking over operations of the site and will relaunch it in early 2025. Excitingly, there are\\u00a0plans to add a new attraction which, naturally, you'd\\u00a0assume is a\\u00a0zip-wire, but the company has confirmed that's not the case.  The company\\u00a0is investing\\u00a0\\u00a32.6 million in the tall red tower and is working with local planning authorities to open 'European first-of-its-kind adventure at Zip World London'.\\u00a0That's all we know at this stage. Do not worry, the slide is not going anywhere.  Andrew Hudson, CEO at Zip World, said: 'This site marks our ninth location in the UK and our first in southeast England, which is a huge milestone for Zip World and what we hope will kick off a whole new era of excitement and adventure right in the heart of London.  'This has the potential to generate increased visitor footfall, economic benefit and employment for the local area. We look forward to seeing plans develop as we prepare to relaunch in early 2025.'  London's always getting new, slightly strange stuff to keep the city's residents intrigued. Recently on Time Out we covered howIslington could get afloating lido in a canal, you will be able to\\u00a0ridethis tiny Underground trainanda brand-new branch of Bao is opening - with karaoke.  Get the latest and greatest from the Big Smoke - from news and reviews to events and trends. Justfollow our Time Out London WhatsApp channel.  Stay in the loop: sign up to ourfree Time Out London newsletterfor the best of the city, straight to your inbox.  Been there, done that? Think again, myfriend.  By entering your email address you agree to ourTerms of UseandPrivacy Policyand consent to receive emails from Time Out about news, events, offers and partner promotions.  \\ud83d\\ude4cAwesome, you are subscribed!  Thanks for subscribing! Look out for your first newsletter in your inbox soon!  Popular on Time Out    Popular on Time Out          Discover Time Out original video    Get us in your inbox  By entering your email address you agree to ourTerms of UseandPrivacy Policyand consent to receive emails from Time Out about news, events, offers and partner promotions.